10 SUMMARY
1111 This amendment replaces the bill. The amendment provides that, beginning July 1,
1122 2025, housing assistance is limited to a maximum of 12 months in a 36-month period.
1133 Current law provides that individuals eligible for emergency general assistance, including
1144 individuals experiencing or facing homelessness, and certain individuals with severe and
1155 persistent mental or physical conditions are exempt from this limitation. The amendment
1166 provides that a municipality may not exceed maximum levels of assistance established
1177 pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 22, section 4305 for an applicant household
1188 for more than 30 days in a 12-month period when assistance is granted for housing. The
1199 amendment also requires the Department of Health and Human Services to reimburse
2200 municipalities and Indian tribes 75% of the direct costs incurred by that municipality or
2211 tribe for costs incurred on or after July 1, 2025 and before July 1, 2027 and that beginning
2222 July 1, 2027, the department must reimburse each municipality and each Indian tribe 80%
2233 of the direct costs incurred by that municipality or tribe for costs incurred on or after July
2244 1, 2027. Finally, the amendment removes the requirement that the department, beginning
2255 July 1, 2025, provide overseers access to an Internet-based, real-time database containing
2266 the information necessary to properly determine eligibility of an applicant for general
2277 assistance.
